The film itself is that sort that the Brits do so well, &quot;a little film&quot; -- character study, working class, interesting without trying to be earthshaking. I suspect that the difficulty of understanding the accents (not just Carlyle's &quot;deepest Glaswegian&quot;, but the several other regional accents (notably &quot;Tony&quot;'s Irish) has contributed to the film's obscurity in the States, but it's well worth seeking out.
